metadata.name: A Strange Loop #300
metadata.description:
[ TAP/CLICK TO ACTIVATE SOUND ]

A whiff of pattern begins to emerge. Out of disarray comes the familiar pulsation of an ordered signal. The sense of regularity strengthens and we feel it swelling towards a singularity. Heeere weeee goooo‚Ä¶ BAM! Then off again marching back into chaos to repeat the cycle.

Proposed by cognitive scientist Douglas Hofstadter in his 1979 book ‚ÄúG√∂del, Escher, Bach‚Äù, and further developed in his 2007 book ‚ÄúI Am a Strange Loop‚Äù, ‚ÄúStrange Loops‚Äù are Hofstadter‚Äôs attempt at explaining the mechanisms that give rise to the sensation of ‚ÄúI‚Äù - through hierarchical, self-referential, and at times seemingly paradoxical feedback-loops of abstraction and causality. 

‚Äî

‚ÄúWho shoves whom around in the tangled megaganglion that is your brain, and who shoves whom around in ‚Äòthis teetering bulb of dread and dream‚Äô that is mine?‚Äù

‚ÄúDo dreads and dreams, hopes and griefs, ideas and beliefs, interests and doubts, infatuations and envies, memories and ambitions, bouts of nostalgia and floods of empathy, flashes of guilt and sparks of genius, play any role in the world of physical objects? Do such pure abstractions have causal powers? Can they shove massive things around, or are they just impotent fictions?‚Äù 

"In the end, we are self-perceiving, self-inventing, locked-in mirages that are little miracles of self-reference. [...] Poised midway between the unvisualizable cosmic vastness of curved spacetime and the dubious, shadowy flickerings of charged quanta, we human beings, more like rainbows and mirages than like raindrops or boulders, are unpredictable self-writing poems ‚Äî vague, metaphorical, ambiguous, and sometimes exceedingly beautiful.‚Äù

- Douglas Hofstadter, ‚ÄúI Am a Strange Loop‚Äù, 2007

‚Äì-

James Paterson 
Synthesizing drawing, animation, sculpture and code under the moniker Presstube since 1999. Inspired by meditation, molecular biology, music, parenting, psychedelics, the seen, the heard, the felt, the cognized.

metadata.name: Oceans of Anxiety #244
metadata.description:
Fully generated by code on your machine. Variety of palletes and styles hand-picked with love and understanding.

Anxiety comes in waves.
It‚Äôs that sense of unidentifiable dread.
It can feel like you‚Äôre in the middle of an ocean on a rocking boat, and on those really bad days there isn‚Äôt even a lifebuoy, you‚Äôre drowning and can‚Äôt catch your breath, time is viscous and moving in slow-motion.

This piece does not set out to necessarily convey only the worst of dealing with anxiety, but also the resolutions and relief when it‚Äôs not there, or finally lets you go.

metadata.name: Tiny Devices #A: Calculator #98
metadata.description:
Genesis piece üßÆ
Fully Functional Interactive SVG Calculators.

Features:
- Themes: J-1, ET-66, ET-55, 903-M, 12C, EL-8, AMDN, 86R, CMBR, PRDT, LGS-9, TI-84, MARK-82, DVSM-18, CCCLTR, SMM-19, DVSM-24, SL-800, W, B
- Configurations: 0, 0x4, 1x3, 2x2, 3x1, 5x0
- Sizes: 5x4, 6x4, 7x4, 8x4, 10x4, 5x5, 6x5, 7x5, 8x5, 5x6, 6x6, 7x6, 5x7, 6x7, 5x8
- Helper: true / false (10% chance, shows operation name for 2 value commands)

Keyboard Shortcuts:
Clear: Delete, Space. Delete: Backspace.
0-9: 0-9, Numpad 0-9. Decimal: Period. Numpad Decimal.
Add: Shift+=, Numpad +. Subtract: -, Numpad -.
Multiply: Shift+8, Numpad -. Divide: /, Numpad /.
Equals: =, Enter, Numpad Enter, Numpad =.
Cut: Ctrl+X. Copy: Ctrl+C. Paste: Ctrl+V.
Negate: Shift+\, Shift+-. Modulo: Shift+5.
Power: Shift+6. Square Root: Q. Y Root X: R. Random: Shift+R. 1 / X: D.
E: E. Logarithm Y X : L. PI: P. Factorial: Shift+1, F.
Sin: S. Cos: C. Tan: T. Arc Toggle: A. Hyperbolic Toggle: H.
Floor: [. Round: \. Ceil: ].

metadata.name: FRAG || DEFRAG #113
metadata.description:
FRAG || DEFRAG is structured from the superposition of simple shapes, such as triangles, that alternate in different layers and blending modes. In this scenario, visual complexity is revealed at different times and intensities, offering countless possibilities of perception.

Along with this, the chromatic variation with unique gradations associated with the play of lights and shadows, gives the project different perspectives and depths, in continuous and complementary cycles of fragmentation and defragmentation.

Thus, as in everything that surrounds us, the resulting form does not end in itself, but presents itself as a result of the combination of several other distinct elements.

Nothing is just one thing.

#Main Features
- 13 color schemes ‚Äúzones‚Äù:

* Shadow Sky and Bronze ‚Äì 12,5% chance
* TIF, Soldier, Zreen and Ice ‚Äì 10% chance each
* Vascai ‚Äì 7,5% chance
* Burn Golden, Gray, Lemonade, REC and BR ‚Äì 5% chance 
* 80‚Äôs ‚Äì 2,5% chance

- 3 canvas formats;
- 3 frequency;
- 2 gradient type;
- 3 degrees of granulometry;

- 1 ultrarare feature | negative effect 

There is only a 1% chance of the negative effect appearing, if you are lucky you will see the following message. "YOU WIN A FREE EDITION OF MY NEXT PROJECT"

Obs.: 
- The first 5 iterations will entitle you to 1 free edition of my next project on FxHash.
- The rendering process should take a few seconds, so enjoy the look of the triangles in action.

July 30, 2022

Generative Token by Morbeck for fxhash.

metadata.name: Holy Mountain #70
metadata.description:
Mountains throughout human history have taken on deep meanings. Coated with immense sacredness by all peoples in the most different places. Being them as a representation of God himself or being the object of worship. For many the mountains were the very abode of the Gods. They are in the collective unconscious as the ability to connect men and gods, through the flow of energy between earth and heaven.

The symbology is very strong. It unconsciously reminds us of the process of encounter between the loneliness of the earth and the hope of the sky, between the fog that blinds and the cloud that supports, between the abyss of the ground and the proximity of the stars. All this is very charming and fascinating.

All human beings have their own mountain, which demands from each one their limits to reach the top, the desire for the breathtaking view, the fear of falling, but also the hope of the last step at the highest point.

In generative art it couldn't be different, going through all the learning, from its fundamentals, to all the countless hours of tests, to countless moments of problem solving and research and more research. This whole process is without a doubt like climbing a mountain. Thinking about the project is exactly like looking at a mountain and imagining how exhausting it will be all the way to conquer it. Finishing your work is like breathing a sigh of relief, looking down and seeing how hard it was to get there, but at the same time looking ahead and realizing how rewarding it was to be able to have that vision and breathe the refreshing breeze of the moment.

After going through a transformation in my first work, where I transmuted my artistic essence from illustration to generative art. Now I come to this second work that I delved into, and after months of climbing this mountain of mine, I give it to you.


- Press "S" in live view mode after loading to save at 1600x1600px.

CC BY-NC-ND 4.0

project website:
https://playman.me/projectmountain

metadata.name: Boom_fx_max #191
metadata.description:
Boom_fx_max, by Stephen Boyd  
August, 2022  
Little India, Toronto, Canada.

This is a free mint for anyone who is a holder of Boom_fx as of August 31, 2022, 00:11:00Z. 

Signed 18" x 12" or 12" x 12" prints are available to holders for both Boom_fx and Boom_fx_max tokens on request. Please send a DM for more information.

Any unclaimed reserves will be released after four days and available at a price to be determined. 


Project Description
---
Boom_fx_max uses all eleven days of data in one image. This constitutes 4,567 earthquakes being represented in every output. This differs from the original Boom_fx which used hours of time on one of the eleven days and typically included a few hundred seismic events.

There are eleven new colour palettes and seven different ratios to organize relationships between visual elements.

The earthquake data comes from the USGS API. There is further documentation (./documentation/Information_about_boom_fx_max.md) included with this project that outlines how this data was collected and the information included in these feeds.


Three Features
---
1. Aspect ratios:
   - Landscape
   - Portrait
   - Square
2. Eleven colour palettes
3. Seven Organizing Principle Ratios:
   - Super Golden Ratio
   - PHI
   - Golden Angle
   - Silver Ratio
   - Euler's Number
   - Reciprocal Fibonacci Constant
   - Feigenbaum Constant


Interaction
---
Export to a PNG format at several different sizes.
- Press t: thumbnail @ a maximum pixel width or height of 200px
- Press s: your current screen size
- Press p: print size @ a maximum pixel width or height of 4800px which is 16"@300dpi
- Press h: HD4K on the vertical @ a maximum pixel width or height of 2160px
- Press m: Max size @ a maximum pixel width or height of 10800px.

The filename will include some metadata such as the unique hash, date and time at time of capture.


Appreciation
---
Thank you to everyone who has collected one my pieces.

Thank you to the USGS for making this data available.

And thank you the most to KIRH.


Data Sources, Software Libraries and VCS / Source Code
--- 
Data Sources
All earthquake data is sourced from the USGS Earthquake API for the International Federation of Digital Seismograph Networks (FDSN). 

Software Libraries Used
Made with Processing / P5.js  
p5.js v1.4.1 February 02, 2022
